video

To do this by hand, you first calculate the sample statistics. \[n_1 = 37\] \[n_2 = 21\] \[\bar{x}_1 = 456\] \[\bar{x}_2 = 443.4\] \[s_1 = 20.6\] \[s_2 = 33.5\] \[|t| = 1.57\] \[\text{df} = 28.775\] You will get quite close if you round df down (floor).

Then, using a computer application or a \(t\) table, you should be able to determine the following probabilities (using interpolation to estimate if using \(t\) table). \[P(T<1.57) = 0.936 \] \[P(|T|>1.57) = 0.128 \] \[p\text{-value} = 0.128 \]

Spreadsheet

You just need to use T.TEST with the proper settings. You can download the solution as a csv.


R

You just use t.test with the default settings. The hardest part is getting the data imported. You can do this in 2 ways: copy/paste or read.csv.

copy/paste

read.csv

Download triglyceride.csv and move it to a directory (folder). Make a script, welchttest.r, and put it in the same directory. Set the working directory to this directory. Then, run the script.

### welchttest.r
data = read.csv("triglyceride.csv")
x1 = data$x1
x2 = data$x2
t.test(x1,x2)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  x1 and x2
## t = 1.5674, df = 28.775, p-value = 0.128
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -3.858796 29.134986
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  456.0000  443.3619
